						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="our-process" id="security">
				<div class="container">
					<div class="row">
						<div class="col-sm-6" data-aos="fade-up">
							<h3 class="text-dark">Additional Security </h3>
							
							<p>Using the technique above, your proxy username and password will be visible to anyone who can view the source of your website. If you have an intranet, and trust your users, then this may be fine, however, we do recommend taking the following security step;
							</p>
							<p>
								You can encrypt your proxy username and password by calling:
							</p>
<pre>
ajaxProxy.Encrypt("password");
</pre>
							<p>
							Which will return a string such as follows
							</p>
<pre>
:ENCRYPTED:H20n0hTqmOduBYNOatwApO1almPAr/ue
</pre>

							<p>

							You can pass this string in place of the username and/or password and the script will do the decryption under the hood. 
							There is no public method to reverse this encryption, so it is not possible for an attacker to reverse engineer your password without stealing our private keys, which we keep secret. 

							</p>

							
						</div>
						<div class="col-sm-6 text-right" data-aos="flip-left" data-aos-easing="ease-out-cubic" data-aos-duration="2000">
							<img src="images/safe.png" alt="security" class="img-fluid">
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>


		

			
			
			
